{{expand}}

A '''god complex''' is a colloquial term used to portray a perceived character flaw as if it was a 'psychological [[complex (psychology)|complex]]'.  The person who is said to have a 'god complex' does not believe he is [[God]], but is said to act so arrogantly that he might as well believe he is a god or appointed to act by a god.  Some people also call it a '''[[messiah]] complex'''.

Some believe that 'god complexes' are "particularly common in arrogant, highly educated, worldly, or powerful people." [http://www.eurolegal.org/terrorism/terror204.htm]

==Scholarly research==

There are few academic works specifically addressing god complexes, although a great deal can be found about [[narcissism]].

According to the book ''All Mighty: A Study of the God Complex in Western Man'', by [[Horst Richter]] (ISBN 0897930282), [[authoritarian]] [[compulsion|compulsions]] are related to the [[rebel|rebellious]] stage of childhood development.  Richter argues that the arrested development of such compulsions leads to denial of suffering, self-doubt, and death, and an expectation of [[servile|servility]] for women and minorities.

==Napoleon Bonaparte==

The [[French Revolution]] may well, in the opinion of some, illustrate the destructiveness of arrogant reforms attributable to god complexes.  The purported God-like intention of intellectuals to reinvent the world, and in particular the retroactively claimed god complex of [[Napoleon I of France|Napoleon Bonaparte]], may have been in some opinions the catalyst for the twenty years of war that ensued.  A collective god complex, rooted in the utopianism of the [[Age of Enlightenment|French Enlightenment]], is considered by some to have led to the reign of terror that afflicted all of Europe beginning in the late 18th century.[http://www.renewamerica.us/analyses/050930hutchison.htm]

